  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price projection tool anchored to a manipulation leg (the swing that sweeps liquidity and triggers a market structure shift or change in state of delivery) within AMD setups, projecting negative standard deviation levels (-1, -2, -2.5, -4, -4.5) as distribution or expansion targets beyond the reversal point. Key levels are plotted at 2–2.5 and 4–4.5 standard deviations from the origin, marking high-probability take-profit zones and maximum expansion areas.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a manipulation leg within an AMD structure: a swing that sweeps a liquidity level (session high/low, equal highs/lows) and is followed by aggressive displacement or a market structure shift (change in state of delivery) back in the opposite direction.",
    "Anchor the Fibonacci projection tool from the manipulation extreme (high for bearish, low for bullish) to the swing point that initiated the manipulation (i.e., the low that created the high, or the high that created the low).",
    "Plot horizontal levels at the negative Fibonacci extensions: -1, -2, -2.5, -4, and -4.5 standard deviations in the direction of the anticipated distribution/expansion.",
    "Confirm that a change in state of delivery or market structure shift has occurred after the manipulation before treating these projections as valid targets.",
    "Cross-reference projection levels with higher time frame draw on liquidity (e.g., previous day high/low, old swing points, equal lows/highs) to select the most probable target level.",
    "If the manipulation leg is disproportionately large, reduce target ambition to the nearest level (-1) rather than deeper extensions.",
    "When projections from multiple manipulation legs or timeframes overlap, treat the overlapping zone as a higher-probability target area.",
    "Use projection levels in conjunction with points of interest (order blocks, fair value gaps) for entry and stop placement, not as standalone targets.",
    "In multi-timeframe analysis, higher timeframe standard deviation levels can be combined with lower timeframe entry points."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Used to set profit targets after a manipulation leg and change in state of delivery, especially when the nearest structural level offers inadequate risk-to-reward. The -2 to -2.5 zone serves as the primary take-profit, while -4 to -4.5 is used for extended runners. The -1 level is a conservative target when the manipulation leg is already large. Targets are more reliable when they align with higher time frame liquidity (previous day high/low, equal highs). Traders plan entries at PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps) with stops beyond the manipulation extreme, scaling out at successive deviation levels.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Anchoring the projection to the wrong swing (e.g., consolidation range high/low, arbitrary points) instead of the manipulation leg that swept liquidity.",
    "Projecting before confirming a change in state of delivery, displacement, or market structure shift after the manipulation.",
    "Selecting target levels without cross-referencing higher time frame structural liquidity (previous day high/low, equal lows/highs).",
    "Targeting deep deviations (-2, -2.5, -4) when the manipulation leg is disproportionately large, making extended targets unrealistic; use shallower targets like -1 instead.",
    "Using projection levels as standalone targets without a confirmed point of interest (order block, fair value gap) for entry.",
    "Expecting price to precisely hit every projected level without accounting for retracements or reactions at intermediate PD arrays.",
    "Failing to wait for price to retrace into a discount zone or point of interest after the manipulation before expecting continuation to deeper targets.",
    "Confusing projection start and end points, using incorrect candle sequences (e.g., from manipulation move low to high instead of failure swing low to high).",
    "Projecting on lower timeframe using manipulation leg from higher timeframe, causing target misalignment."
  ],
